esponsive CSS grid with SVG progress indicators. I'm focusing on those three scenarios side-by-side using interactive overlays. The idea is to make the experience feel really tactile and custom.\n\n\n\n**Optimizing Interaction Dynamics**\n\nI'm now zeroing in on the interaction strategy. I'm prioritizing real-time responsiveness; adjusting inputs instantly updates both waterfall charts and scenario comparisons. We could compile, showing a cool compiling screen before revealing the full report, or provide direct modifications to the results screen. A dynamic split layout (input/results) with interactive animations feels like the best approach.\n\n\n**Implementing Core Features**\n\nI'm now implementing the core features. I've designed a \"copy to clipboard\" feature that generates a beautiful Markdown executive summary and a reset button to restore default input values. I'm also adding seamless navigation CTAs to other relevant tools. I'm working on a mobile strategy with a single-column layout, swipeable sliders, and fluid typography. The focus is now on `app/build/roi/page.tsx`. I will avoid changes to any landing page files or existing API directories.\n\n\n**Defining Scenarios Mathematically**\n\nI'm now nailing down scenario definitions. The \"Expected\" scenario mirrors the `calculateROIEstimate` baseline with 85% efficiency. \"Conservative\" uses 50% efficiency gain. \"Aggressive\" includes 100% wasted hours recovery *plus* a 20% productivity boost. I've got the equations in place, now focusing on deterministic calculation with the GFF estimate as the base.\n\n\n"}}
